e memory consumption\n- node disk read I/O consumption \n- node disk write I/O consumption \n- node disk space consumption\n\nAnomaly Cluster Description:\nHere is the RCA analysis result in plain English:\n\n```\n{\n  "Cluster 1": {\n    "Key Findings": [\n      "A sustained anomaly was detected on the \'sr\' metric of the checkoutservice-grpc entity, with 8 anomalies within a 9-minute window.",\n      "The adservice.ts:8088 entity experienced garbage collection issues, with 4 anomalies in the same time frame.",\n      "Container memory failures were observed on node-5.shippingservice2-0, with 7 anomalies during this period."\n    ],\n    "Related Entities": [\n      "checkoutservice-grpc",\n      "adservice.ts:8088",\n      "node-5.shippingservice2-0"\n    ],\n    "Possible Root Causes": [\n      "Insufficient memory allocation or garbage collection issues in the adservice.ts:8088 entity.",\n      "Container memory failures on node-5.shippingservice2-0, potentially caused by resource constraints or misconfiguration."\n    ]\n  }\n}\n```\n\nNote that I\'ve condensed the information from the original report into a concise summary of key findings, related entities, and possible root causes.\n\nRelevant Historical Incidents (if any):\n[Past Incident 1] (Score: 0.481)\nComponent: recommendationservice | Metrics: HTTP, gRPC, latency, network, rr, rt, trace\nSummary: Component: recommendationservice\nEvent: recommendationservice failure at 2022-03-20 11:35:26\nSystem Type: Banking Microservice (service)\nSymptoms: container network packet corruption; A log anomaly with the template \'at io.grpc.internal.SerializingExecutor.run(SerializingExecutor.java:123)\' was reported in the \'frontend-2\' pod at 2022-03-20 11:35:00 CST. This timestamp aligns perfe; The \'frontend\' service is a primary upstream caller for various services, including \'recommendationservice\'. The gRPC error is a direct symptom of its inability to communicate with a downstream servic; There is a significant lack of direct metric or trace anomalies associated with \'recommendationservice\'. This absence suggests the failure occurred at a layer below typical application and service mes\nAffected Metrics: HTTP, gRPC, latency, network, rr, rt, trace\nRoot Cause Category: The root cause of the incident was container network packet corruption within the \'recommendationservice\'. This low-level network fault was not direct\nFailure Pattern: The root cause of the incident was container network packet corruption within the \'recommendationservice\'. This low-level network fault was not directly observed through metric anomalies on the service itself. The failure\'s impact was detected upstream in the \'frontend\' service, which experienced gRPC internal errors at the precise time of the incident, indicating a communication breakdown with a downstream dependency, confirmed to be \'recommendationservice\'.\nMitigation Principles: The primary issue is a lack of visibility into low-level network health. To prevent recurrence and improve detection, we should: 1) Implement enhanced container-level network monitoring to track and alert on metrics like packet drops and transmission errors (e.g., `container_network_receive_packets_dropped`, `container_network_transmit_errors_total`). 2) Improve application resilience and diagnostics by ensuring client services log the specific downstream service they are failing to communicate with during RPC errors. 3) Review and augment the anomaly detection system to include these new network-level metrics to close the current visibility gap.\n\nBackgroud:\n"\n\n\nBased on this information, identify the MOST LIKELY root cause component and reason from the candidate list.\nFollow these rules:\n- The root cause must be a single component from the candidate list.\n- The reason must be directly supported by the anomaly description.\n- Assign a suspicious score between 0.0 and 1.0 (higher = more confident).\n\nRespond ONLY with a JSON object in th